[0.462, "o", "\u001b[35D\u001b[27mh\u001b[27me\u001b[27ma\u001b[27md\u001b[27m \u001b[27m-\u001b[27m5\u001b[27m0\u001b[27m \u001b[27mr\u001b[27me\u001b[27ms\u001b[27me\u001b[27ma\u001b[27mr\u001b[27mc\u001b[27mh\u001b[27m-\u001b[27mo\u001b[27mu\u001b[27mt\u001b[27mp\u001b[27mu\u001b[27mt\u001b[27ms\u001b[27m/\u001b[27mo\u001b[27mp\u001b[27me\u001b[27mn\u001b[27ma\u001b[27mi\u001b[27m.\u001b[27mm\u001b[27md\u001b[?2004l\r\r\n"]
[0.003, "o", "Paxos  \r\n• Consensus is reached through a two-phase protocol (Prepare/Promise, Accept/Accepted) among proposers, acceptors, and learners; no fixed leader is required, but a “distinguished proposer” is often used to avoid livelock.  \r\n• Handles any number of crash-failures ⩽ ⌊(N-1)/2⌋; safety is guaranteed despite message delays, reordering, or duplication, but liveness depends on eventually choosing a stable leader and majority of functioning nodes.  \r\n• Mathematically minimal: proves that any correct single-value consensus must include equivalent quorum intersecting properties; however, its roles/messages make real-world implementations subtle and hard to understand.\r\n\r\nRaft  \r\n• Explicitly designed for understandability: decomposes the problem into leader election, log replication, and safety; always operates with exactly one elected leader per term, simplifying normal-case communication to leader↔followers.  \r\n• Uses randomized election timeouts to quickly elect a new leader after cra"]
[0.000, "o", "shes; log entries are replicated via AppendEntries RPCs that piggy-back heartbeats, providing linearizability as long as a majority is alive.  \r\n• Adds practical details (cluster membership changes via joint consensus, log compaction via snapshots) and is widely adopted (etcd, Consul, Rafter, CockroachDB) because its state-machine approach is easier to implement and verify.\r\n\r\nViewstamped Replication (VSR)  \r\n• Pre-dates Raft (1988/1990) and closely resembles it conceptually: the system moves through numbered “views” with a designated primary; backups replicate client requests and acknowledge; if the primary fails, a view-change elects a new one.  \r\n• Separates normal operation, view change, and recovery phases; relies on a majority quorum to make progress, achieving the same safety/liveness properties as Paxos/Raft under crash failures and reliable links with eventual synchrony.  \r\n• Provides a clear protocol for read-only optimizations (clients can read from primaries) and was influential in pra"]
[0.000, "o", "ctical systems (HARBOR, PBFT’s structure); recent “VRR” revisions tighten the spec and simplify recovery, but adoption is less widespread than Raft."]
